# Approach (Two-Tree Recursion)

## Key Idea

Compare both trees **node by node**.

For every pair of nodes:

1. Their values must be equal.
2. Their left subtrees must be identical.
3. Their right subtrees must be identical.

If all three conditions are true, the trees are the same.

---

# Recursive Formula ⭐

```text id="st100j"
SameTree(p, q)

=

(p.val == q.val)

AND

SameTree(p.left, q.left)

AND

SameTree(p.right, q.right)
```

---

## Base Cases

### Case 1

Both nodes are `null`.

```text id="st100k"
null

null
```

Return:

```text id="st100l"
true
```

Both trees ended at the same time.

---

### Case 2

One node is `null`.

```text id="st100m"
5

null
```

Return:

```text id="st100n"
false
```

The structures are different.

---

### Case 3

Values are different.

```text id="st100o"
4

7
```

Return:

```text id="st100p"
false
```

The trees are not identical.

---

## Algorithm

### Step 1

If both nodes are `null`, return `true`.

```java id="st100q"
if(p == null && q == null)
    return true;
```

---

### Step 2

If one node is `null`, return `false`.

```java id="st100r"
if(p == null || q == null)
    return false;
```

---

### Step 3

If the node values are different, return `false`.

```java id="st100s"
if(p.val != q.val)
    return false;
```

---

### Step 4

Recursively compare:

* Left subtree with Left subtree.
* Right subtree with Right subtree.

```java id="st100t"
return isSameTree(p.left, q.left)
    && isSameTree(p.right, q.right);
```

