## Key Learning

* Compare two trees simultaneously.
* Both trees must have:

  * The same structure.
  * The same values.
* Use recursion to compare corresponding nodes.
* This is called the **Two-Tree Recursion Pattern**.

---

## Common Mistakes

❌ Forgetting the case where both nodes are `null`.

Always write:

```java id="st100af"
if(p == null && q == null)
    return true;
```

---

❌ Comparing only node values.

Even if values match, the tree structures must also match.

---

❌ Comparing the wrong child nodes.

For **Same Tree**, always compare:

```java id="st100ag"
p.left  ↔ q.left

p.right ↔ q.right
```

Do **not** compare crossed children (that's used in Symmetric Tree).

---

❌ Forgetting recursive checks.

Checking only the root node is not enough.

Every subtree must also be identical.

---

## Pattern Recognition

Whenever a problem asks you to:

* Compare two trees
* Check if trees are identical
* Verify subtree equality

Think:

```java id="st100ah"
solve(node1, node2)
```

Compare:

* Current node values
* Left subtree with Left subtree
* Right subtree with Right subtree

This is the **Two-Tree Recursion Pattern**.

---

## Takeaway

The key idea is to compare both trees **simultaneously**. At every recursive call, ensure that the current nodes have the same value, their left subtrees are identical, and their right subtrees are identical. If all recursive comparisons succeed, the trees are the same. This problem is the foundation of the **Two-Tree Recursion Pattern**, which is commonly used in Binary Tree interview questions.
